description.text:
The project proposes concealing a GPS tracker inside the top cover of the Teal™ Sport drone. There are several advantages of having an additional tracker independent from the drone electronics. Firstly, its power is independent from the drone's battery supply, GPS tracking abilities won't go idle in case of running out of power while piloting.

Also, in case of theft, a concealed tracker would prevent the drone from being untrackable in case the electronics are disconnected from its power supply or turned off. The tracker attaches to the inner side of the top cover.

Note: The proposal is modeled after the Tile™ Mate tracker and its dimensions but can be altered for any other brand or proprietary electronics from Teal™. The Tile™ Mate was used for representation purposes and proof of concept and no copyright infringement is intended.

description.text:
An initial concept design for a spinning electrophoresis device. One disc-electrode is connected to the central well, and 8 other electrodes are connected around the outer edge of the device. A voltage potential is set up such that charged molecules will head towards one of the outer electrodes at a given time, and a timed counter circuit switches the connected outer electrode at a defined rate (pulse-width modulation could be used to simulate a continuous path around the outer edge).

This device acts as a filter to exclude small charged molecules. At zero rotation speed, all charged molecules will end up in the outer ring. As the speed of current rotation is increased, larger molecules will have insufficient inertia to move all the way to the ring before the current direction changes, and will remain in the central area.

I modified a BASIC program from the July 1984 edition of Creative Computing magazine to run under Chipmunk Basic on my Mac.
I modified the code to save a text file with the coordinates for each line's end points.
I then created a blank SVG file with Inkscape. I opened the SVG in a Sublime text editor and created a polygon with the coordinates from my program.
I then loaded the SVG file into Inkscape and exported it as an Open SCAD file. From there I exported it as an STL file.
You can find the original BASIC source code here: https://archive.org/details/creativecomputing-1984-07 BASIC source code and rudimentary documentation is included.

description.text:
This is a customizable thing that can be used to measure the distance between the rods on an axis. I designed this as I needed a way to find out what the X-carriage dimensions of my no-name Chinese printer were. It's not particularly easy to measure with calipers, and you need it to be exact, so here is a thing that'll confirm the dimensions for you.

First take your digital calipers and measure the rod diameter. It'll probably be a metric rod of 8mm or 10mm diameter. Unless you know it's not metric, round the measured distance to the nearest whole number, so if you get 7.8 or 8.2 use 8.0.

Next measure the distance between the rods, on the inside from the top of one rod to the bottom of the other rod. This is the bit that may need a bit of trial and error, and a few reprints. At the bottom of this page is a table of the dimensions of various printers, so you may be able to avoid printing anything and just look there. If your printer isn't on the list, please add a comment and I'll update it!

To confirm fitting, you probably want to print the next size (0.5mm accuracy seems good enough) up or down as well. The perfect fit should go on easily without much force, slide fairly well, there shouldn't be any stretching (look for a gap between the rod and circular part of measuring tool), and come off without too much force.

Any

No

No

0.3

Notes:

Walls thickness can be 1 layer or vase mode. It's best not to use any build plate adhesion, as that may affect the size.

Known Printer X-Carriage Dimensions

Diameter - Diameter of rod (left number on tool)
Distance - Distance between rods, from the top of one rod to the bottom of the other rod (right number on tool)
Center - Distance between the centers of each rod (Distance + Diameter)

Diameter = 8.0mm, Distance = 36.5mm, Center = 44.5mm
Original Prusa i3
Anycubic Prusa i3
Anet A8 (2016 and earlier)

Diameter = 8.0mm, Distance = 37.0mm, Center = 45.0mm
Anet A8 (late 2016 onwards)

If your printer isn't on the list, once you've measured it using this tool, please add a comment and I'll add it!

title: Alienoid - King of Tokyo
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Alienoid from King of Tokyo. Designed to replace the cardboard cutout that comes with the game. Some assembly required.

Since the transparent bubble helmet that Alienoid is supposed to have does not lend itself well to printing, I decided Alienoid doesn't need one. It can breathe oxygen just fine.

There are three options for printing:

  • SINGLE - The full model in a single file. This may be very tricky to print.
  • FULL (+COMMON) - The model sliced in to few pieces, easier to print, but must be assembled afterwards
  • FLAT (+COMMON) - These files are the easiest to print, as overhangs have been minimized, but there's a lot of assembly to do after printing.

If you print the FULL or the FLAT files, you'll need the COMMON files as well.

As another option, there is a variant file for the "chest-top" part. In "alienoid-chest-top-with-helmet.stl" the Alienoid has a kind of a half-helmet, on which you could possibly glue half a transparent plastic sphere to act as a visor. I haven't tried printing this version, since I haven't been able to find a source for the visor. Leave a comment if you print it!

A few of the parts were sourced from other people's work: The left fist is remixed from Tardis Transformer V2 by Ellindsey, and the ray gun was created with MikeNeame's Customizable Ray Gun. The claws are repurposed T-Rex teeth from sk8nmike's scanned T-rex model.

You can find the rest of the King of Tokyo monsters in this collection. There is also a blog post with more information about the models.

Assembly

The parts need to be glued together. I printed my parts in ABS, and used ABS slurry to glue the parts together.

Pay attention to the orientation of the "thigh" parts when gluing them on the "pelvis" part. It's easy enough to glue the legs in a position where the poor Alienoid can't stand on its three legs. The correct orientations are as follows: The left thigh should point forward, the right thigh should point backwards, and the back thigh should point to the left. Once the thighs are solidly glued on, add the shins and adjust their orientation to give Alienoid a stable stance. Take into account that the arms, once attached, will shift the center of gravity forward.

Test fit each part before applying glue; The parts may need minor filing or sanding to fit.

This is a bracket for attaching rain gutters to walls for vertical gardening. You can fill the gutter with dirt and grow that way or fill it with rocks and use it for hydroponics or aquaponics. However you like to grow your food just make sure to grow more of it! Video of the system in action: https://vimeo.com/45814238

-Required pieces for one assembled bracket-
Qty 1: 1/4 X 1-1/4 washers
Qty 2: 10x1 wood screws
Qty 1: 3d printed rain gutter mounting bracket
Qty 1: twine or wire (if filling the gutter with rocks instead of dirt) -Parts required for one 10 foot length of gutter-
Qty 3: bracket + screws + twine/wire if needed
Qty 1: home depot vinyl rain gutter
Qty 2: home depot vinyl rain gutter end caps -Assembly-
Drill holes in the front face of the gutter end cap that will be on the low side(the draining side). Attach to a fence using the screws and a washer on the top screw. If you use a cup of water and pour it down the gutter then you can see which way the water is going to flow and alternate the gutters so the watter flows down the fence from one gutter to the next. If you are filling the gutters with rocks for hydro or aquaponics then you will need to reinforce each bracket with some twine or wire running under the gutter, through the front hole on the bracket, and back to the wall mount. That lets you hold the gutter tight against the wall instead of having it lean out too far. -Todo-

description.text:
Gigazaur from King of Tokyo. Designed to replace the cardboard cutout that comes with the game. Some assembly required.

There are three options for printing:

  • SINGLE - The full model in a single file. This may be very tricky to print.
  • FULL (+COMMON) - The model sliced in to few pieces, easier to print, but must be assembled afterwards
  • FLAT (+COMMON) - These files are the easiest to print, as overhangs have been minimized, but there's a lot of assembly to do after printing.

If you print the FULL or the FLAT files, you'll need the COMMON files as well.

For printing the front half of the torso, I manually added supports in Gigazaur's teeth. Due to the overhangs in the area, printing without supports will be difficult.

The teeth and claws were copied from sk8nmike's scanned T-rex model.

You can find the rest of the King of Tokyo monsters in this collection. There is also a blog post with more information about the models.

Assembly

The parts need to be glued together. I printed my parts in ABS, and used ABS slurry to glue the parts together.

Test fit each part before applying glue; The parts may need minor filing or sanding to fit.

title: DIY Filament Dryer / Dehydrator, Tweaked v2.0

description.text:
Shortly after creating my first filament dehydrator https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2520281, I found CreativeTools' Filament Spool Holder. My first version worked fine, but I found some shavings on the spool holder when changing filaments, caused by the friction between the holder and the spool. Also, my original holder was only sized for certain spools, not as universal as I had expected. Not a big deal, but I'm a big fan of maximum efficiency...so here you go, a slightly better version than the first.

Here are the links I had in my first version: Dehydrator: https://www.amazon.com/Flexzion-Dehydrator-Food-Fruit-Dehydration/dp/B01J51JLCC/ref=sr_1_23?s=kitchen&ie=UTF8&qid=1499306986&sr=1-23&keywords=dehydrator+machine
and Wilton's cake caddy, which I got from Joann http://www.joann.com/cake-caddy/5717806.html#q=cake%2Bcaddy&start=1, for about $10 (don't forget to use your coupons!)

  • I recently found out that Flexzion is currently out of stock on Amazon. I know for sure that the nutrichef PKFD14 (and 14BK) are not the right size for the caddy, but perhaps it will work with Westinghouse http://amzn.to/2Bsxth4 or Rosewill http://amzn.to/2HdMbJj.
  • You could use Dr. Boo's Filament Dryer Spacers https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2797196 with a 5-star Chef Food Dehydrator, but since the walls are not clear, you won't be able to see how much filament you have left.

The only other thing you need is 2 #4 x 5/8" pan head screws. You could use another dehydrator and top, there are suggestions on Tinkerman's original dehydrator page: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1618037

I didn't mess with CreativeTools' duster, the filament is in an enclosed space, not likely to gather dust. My snoot is intended for a PC4-M6 Male Straight Pneumatic Connector. The PTFE tube keeps the air from reaching the filament before it reaches the printer and keeps the filament from crimping.

Special thanks goes to CreativeTools and Tinkerman for sharing their original ideas!

*Tip: Be sure to have the dehydrator sitting on a flat surface with no holes. If there's too much air flow from underneath, it won't get hot and can eventually burn out the heating unit (a resistor I think?).

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

.25 for large objects, .1 for small

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Printed the snoot .1, only with base supports. The threads printed a little warped without full supports, but it still worked for me.

The base and spool will need to fit into each other, I recommend testing your printer with https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2648645 to make sure your calibration is good.

I threw some dessicant in the dehydrator under the spool, it helps to keep the humidity down when it's off.

I also got a timer to turn on the dehydrator 2 or 3 times a day, 2 hours each, to keep any moisture from coming in. I recommend an electrical, the mechanical ones can be pretty noisy.

title: Better Belt Clip for Behringer Powerplay P1 In-Ear Monitor
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The stock belt clip of the (otherwise very priceworthy) Behringer Powerplay P1 is placed very low down (see image), which makes the unit top-heavy. The gap is also very wide, so the mixer tends to tip over and flop around if you try to keep it on you guitar strap. I've even had it fall off a couple of times during a gig.

This is an improved design that keeps the mixer's center of mass below the belt (no pun intended), while gripping the belt tighter due to a smaller gap.

Non Printable Parts

2x short M2 screws. These are not strictly necessary, but highly recommended.

Assembly

After breaking off the supports (all the ugly scratches you see is me cutting and drilling), put two short M2 (2mm diameter) screws into the holes at the back of the mixer. The heads should fit into the larger holes of the belt clip. The purpose of these is to prevent the clip from rotating. Make sure the screws are short enough not to touch the circuit board underneath! M2 x 6mm should be ok, that's what I have.

Put the clip into place and push in the large tubular screw. Find some suitable tool and tighten it. Ready to rock!

This is an 8.5" by 11" picture frame, made of 4 types of pieces and a total of 20 parts. This was modeled to be compatible with very small printers and if you have a larger one then it will be no problem to print multiple pieces at once. I recommend a wood-fill filament as you can stain it fairly easily. Also, if you slice this in the latest version of Cura, there is a setting called Print ironing that I highly recommend you try.

You will need: 6 of the side pieces, 4 of each corner (no, you can't print 8 of one, trust me), and as many tabs as you think necessary.

Obviously by adding more side pieces this can be infinitely scaled up, but the minimum size for this frame would be a 6"x 6" square.

title: Ryobi Fixed Line String Trimmer Head

description.text:
I have the Ryobi ELT1100A 1100W electric trimmer which I hated the bumpfeed head it came with and wanted to replace it with a fixed line head.
There are few fixed line replacement heads on the market but I thought I'd make my own.

I used the MTM 3.1mm Pre-Cut 35cm Trimmer Line from https://www.edisons.com.au/orange-35cm-100-pcs-pre-cut-square-edge-trimmer-line/
The head can be used with smaller square or round lines.
When mounted the 35cm line is ideal length for this head.

Initial prototype printed using ABS with the following settings,
Layer Heiht: 0.2mm
Shell Thickness: 0.8mm
Fill Density: 15%
Print Temp: 240C
Bed Temp: 100C
Fan: Off

Although printed at 15% fill density to test the fit, I ended up using it for a day and it worked a treat.

I will be printing another head with 75% density and thicker walls as a final product. Knob printed at 100% density for extra durability.

The Ryobi ELT1100A did get a little warm on a 30 degree day with the additional thicker line, but it did well for about 2 hour of continuous work.
